      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.5666365,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9f37933d-ed50-4c6b-bfd6-31f213fb9caf",
        "score": 0.5535769,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to the sale and purchase of Unforced Capacity in the New York ISO market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Market-Clearing Prices**: \n   - Sellers of Unforced Capacity are paid based on the Market-Clearing Price for their locality, the New York Control Area (NYCA), or an external control area, multiplied by the number of megawatts (MW) of accepted offers.\n\n2. **ICAP Spot Market Auction**: \n   - Entities purchasing Unforced Capacity are charged according to the Market-Clearing Price as detailed in Section 5.15 of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Billing and Payment Schedule**: \n   - Settlements occur in the month following the purchase. For example, capacity bought in May is billed in June. The billing schedule aligns with the Energy Market schedule, available on the NYISO website.\n\n4. **Six-Month Strip Auction**: \n   - Unforced Capacity purchased in this auction is settled monthly, with bills issued for one-sixth of the applicable Market-Clearing Price.\n\n5. **Allocation of Winning Bids**: \n   - During Capability Period and Monthly Auctions, bidders specifying a locality for their Unforced Capacity will receive a pro rata share of the purchased capacity.\n\nThis document is part of the Installed Capacity Manual, providing detailed guidelines for market participants.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_243.jpg",
          "page_num": 243,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "69c4d233-0773-4b95-b4b3-76405f5ddae8",
        "score": 0.55062354,
        "text": "The document page discusses the monthly average net imports into Long Island for 2022-2023, focusing on three transmission interfaces: Cross Sound Cable, Neptune, and Northport-Norwalk. The graph shows peak and off-peak net imports, with data indicating an increase in average peak imports from 2022 to 2023 for Neptune and Northport-Norwalk, while Cross Sound Cable shows a decrease.\n\nThe text explains the importance of price convergence and efficient scheduling with adjacent markets for New York's wholesale electricity markets. Efficient use of transmission interfaces helps in arbitraging price differences between regions, ensuring resources are used optimally. Inefficient use can lead to higher costs and reliability issues. However, several factors hinder full arbitrage, such as lack of foresight, differences in scheduling procedures, and transaction costs. These factors prevent market participants from fully optimizing the use of interfaces.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_258.jpg",
          "page_num": 258,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0f4e4c04-660d-4344-a06e-7957b5a3fcff",
        "score": 0.548375,
        "text": "The document discusses several key issues related to the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO) and its operations:\n\n1. **Export Fees and CTS Transactions**: NYISO's high export fees, amounting to $0.8 million in 2021, may reduce revenues from Coordinated Transaction Scheduling (CTS) transactions. Lower fees could increase profitability. The document suggests reducing transaction fees and uplift charges between PJM and NYISO to improve effectiveness.\n\n2. **Price Forecast Errors**: Errors at interfaces affect the effectiveness of CTS processes. Improving these processes is crucial for handling renewable output growth and balancing short-term fluctuations in intermittent generation.\n\n3. **PAR-Controlled Lines**: Phase angle regulators (PARs) are used to manage production costs. The operation of lines between Long Island and New York City increased costs and emissions in 2021. The report recommends exploring changes to the ConEd-LIPA wheeling agreement to enhance efficiency, especially with the growth of offshore wind and intermittent generation.\n\n4. **Out-of-Market Actions**: Guarantee payments to generators increased by 28% to $54 million in 2021, mainly due to higher natural gas prices. This was partially offset by reduced out-of-market commitments and dispatches.\n\nOverall, the document emphasizes the need for operational improvements and cost reductions to enhance efficiency and accommodate renewable energy growth.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2021/page_16.jpg",
          "page_num": 16,
          "title": "2021 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c7f7e1ea-c08e-41ea-b01d-dcd29aa88bd9",
        "score": 0.54588777,
        "text": "The document page is from the New York ISO Aggregation Manual and includes a table of contents for sections 5 to 7. Here's a summary:\n\n### Section 5: Transmission Nodes\n- **5.1**: Discusses member system topology considerations and the active transmission node list.\n- **5.2**: Covers transmission node changes, including the change timeline.\n- **5.3**: Details DER (Distributed Energy Resource) designation to a transmission node and related changes.\n- **5.4**: Focuses on transmission node operations.\n- **5.5**: Outlines aggregator responsibilities.\n\n### Section 6: Operational Coordination\n- **6.1**: Describes operating data exchange, including planned and unplanned system maintenance, market bids, outage reporting, and dispatch instructions.\n- **6.2**: Defines roles and responsibilities, emphasizing communication between various entities like distribution utilities, transmission owners, aggregators, and NYISO.\n- **6.3**: Provides a coordination timeline for dispatch activities, detailing specific timeframes for actions before and after dispatch.\n\n### Section 7: Metering & Telemetry\n- **7.1**: Offers background information.\n- **7.2**: Lists metering requirements.\n- **7.3**: Details telemetry requirements, including a specific telemetry testing procedure for NYISO-member systems.\n\nThis page outlines the structure and key topics covered in these sections of the manual.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Aggregation_Manual/page_4.jpg",
          "page_num": 4,
          "title": "Aggregation Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

