steps.content:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "NYISO generation interconnection process manual application deposit study fees",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "NYISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "9a7044c5-f6d8-442f-8620-8b17231a60b3",
        "score": 0.58895165,
        "text": "The document discusses the evaluation of market incentives for modeling N-1-1 requirements in New York City's day-ahead market by estimating clearing prices for 2018. It presents a summary of results for four NYC locations: the 345kV network in Staten Island, Astoria West/Queensbridge, Vernon, and Greenwood/Staten Island. The table shows average marginal commitment costs, with prices ranging from $2.01/MWh for the NYC 345 kV System to $5.18/MWh for Astoria West/Queensbridge.\n\nThe analysis indicates that satisfying N-1-1 requirements would lead to price increases, with costs varying from $2.01 to $5.18 per MWh. These increases are additional to existing reserve product prices in Southeast New York. The document also examines the impact on energy and reserve net revenues if units were compensated for reserves at these rates.\n\nRecommendations include modeling N-1-1 constraints in NYC load pockets to enhance market efficiency and reliability. The NYISO plans to introduce a 10-minute and a 30-minute reserve product for NYC in mid-2019, aiming for more efficient scheduling and pricing.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2018/page_116.jpg",
          "page_num": 116,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e265fb5b-5098-4f8a-8529-b45dfcab7939",
        "score": 0.5774496,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York, categorized by region and year (2018-2019). The chart shows costs in millions of dollars for New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports, with a total for each year. In 2019, the total was $52 million, down from $77 million in 2018. Long Island's costs remained stable at $15 million each year, with a significant portion (67%) attributed to high-cost peaking resources managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations include modeling specific constraints to improve market efficiency and reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_125.jpg",
          "page_num": 125,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a7d43ff1-4d13-404c-8b4b-0d2edc71769d",
        "score": 0.5760511,
        "text": "The document discusses the reduction in total guarantee payment uplift costs, which fell by 32% from $77 million in 2018 to $52 million in 2019. This decrease was attributed to reduced supplemental commitments in New York City, lower gas prices, and decreased load levels during summer months. New York City accounted for $29 million (55%) of the BPCG in 2019, with over $21 million paid to generators for N-1-1 local requirements. Recommendations were made to adjust NYISO's local reserve requirements to improve efficiency. Long Island accounted for $15 million (28%) of BPCG, with nearly $10 million related to managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations were also made for modeling constraints in Long Island's markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_332.jpg",
          "page_num": 332,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7e1da819-1e4b-42d9-b76b-7225657a28dc",
        "score": 0.57145524,
        "text": "The document outlines the procedures and requirements for submitting DMNC (Dependable Maximum Net Capability) or DMGC (Dependable Maximum Generating Capacity) test data or data from actual operations to the New York ISO (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Submission Requirements**: Failure to submit the required data or a completed supplemental form may result in financial penalties.\n\n2. **Purpose**: The data is used to establish a generating resource's Installed Capacity value, which is adjusted according to specific sections of the ICAP Manual.\n\n3. **Validation Process**: Submitted data must be complete and in an acceptable format. NYISO will validate and approve or reject the data within 30 days.\n\n4. **Discrepancies**: Any discrepancies between submitted data and NYISO billing information must be resolved through an audit process within the 30-day period.\n\n5. **Approval and Rejection**: If approved, the data is valid for the current Capability Period. If rejected, the supplier can resubmit data, accept NYISO's determined value, or request an audit.\n\n6. **Audit Process**: If an audit is requested, NYISO will work with the supplier. If the audit supports the supplier's data, the original rating remains. If not, the supplier must resubmit data, and deficiency charges may apply.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_85.jpg",
          "page_num": 85,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "43f20e2d-6be7-4d24-9080-34e7efa1062b",
        "score": 0.5696144,
        "text": "The document discusses pricing and settlement methods for capacity resources in Zone J, focusing on resource adequacy and transmission security. It outlines a scenario where the incremental price for resource adequacy is $5.60 per kW-month, and for transmission security, it's $7.50 per kW-month. Most Zone J resources receive the full clearing price of $19 per kW-month, while others receive $11.50 based on resource adequacy.\n\nThree hypothetical resources are illustrated:\n\n1. SCRs receive $11.50 per kW-month.\n2. A 1000 MW generator is paid for 720 MW at $19 per kW-month and 230 MW at $11.50.\n3. An 800 MW offshore wind unit is paid for 200 MW at $11.50 and 80 MW at $7.50.\n\nThe document recommends a two-part pricing method to separate payments for resource adequacy and transmission security, aiming to improve investment incentives and reduce overpayments.\n\nAdditionally, it critiques the NYISO's deliverability test methodology, noting its misalignment with resource adequacy analyses and its potential impact on estimating resources' deliverability as renewables and storage grow.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_371.jpg",
          "page_num": 371,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

